CHANGES TO IMPLEMENT

1. CREATE ONE EXPLICIT STUBBED DATA LAYER

Create one structured stubbed data source for the prototype.

This stubbed data layer must be the only source for:
- controls state
- breadcrumb state
- scope text
- KPI summaries
- table rows
- drill states
- excluded logic
- pivot permutations
- metric permutations
- spend mode permutations
- timeframe and view-by permutations

Do not keep duplicate mock data sources.

2. USE THIS EXACT TOP-LEVEL SHAPE

Create the stubbed data layer with these top-level sections:

- reportState
- optionSets
- entities
- reportViews

Use these names exactly.

3. DEFINE reportState EXACTLY AS FOLLOWS

reportState must contain:

- pivotBy
- timeframe
- viewBy
- metric
- spendMode
- tableSize
- breadcrumbPath
- scopeLabel
- activeViewId

Meaning:
- pivotBy: current pivot selection
- timeframe: current reporting span
- viewBy: current partition of the selected timeframe
- metric: PPD or Dollars
- spendMode: Actual, Commitment, or Total Impact
- tableSize: current density / size mode
- breadcrumbPath: ordered list of visible breadcrumb segments
- scopeLabel: visible scope line text
- activeViewId: the current report view record to render

4. DEFINE optionSets EXACTLY AS FOLLOWS

optionSets must contain:

- pivotByOptions
- timeframeOptions
- viewByOptions
- metricOptions
- spendModeOptions
- tableSizeOptions

Use these values:

pivotByOptions
- Facility
- GL Account
- Vendor

timeframeOptions
- Last 7 Days
- Last 30 Days
- Month to Date
- Last Month
- Quarter to Date
- Last Quarter
- Year to Date
- Last 12 Months
- Custom Range

viewByOptions
- Daily
- Weekly
- Monthly
- Quarterly

metricOptions
- PPD
- Dollars

spendModeOptions
- Actual
- Commitment
- Total Impact

tableSizeOptions
- Compact
- Standard
- Comfortable

5. DEFINE entities EXACTLY AS FOLLOWS

entities must contain:

- facilities
- glAccounts
- vendors
- transactions

Each facility record must contain:
- id
- name

Each glAccount record must contain:
- id
- code
- name
- displayName
- excluded

displayName must be:
[GL Code] - [GL Account Name]

Each vendor record must contain:
- id
- name

Each transaction record must contain:
- id
- label
- type
- date

Do not invent additional entity types unless they are required internally and remain invisible.

6. DEFINE reportViews EXACTLY AS FOLLOWS

reportViews must be a collection of renderable report states.

Each report view record must contain:

- id
- breadcrumbPath
- scopeLabel
- kpis
- rows

Each kpis object must contain:
- totalBudget
- totalConsumed
- totalVariance
- variancePercent

Each row record must contain:

- id
- entityType
- entityId
- label
- budget
- spend
- variance
- variancePercent
- status
- excluded
- childViewId
- timeBuckets

Use these meanings:

- entityType: Facility, GL Account, Vendor, or Transaction
- entityId: references the matching entity record
- label: the visible first-column value
- budget: numeric value or null when excluded
- spend: numeric value
- variance: numeric value or null when excluded
- variancePercent: numeric value or null when excluded
- status: Healthy, Over Budget, Excluded, or other already-established state
- excluded: true or false
- childViewId: the next drill view if drillable
- timeBuckets: bucketed values for active View By rendering

7. DEFINE EXCLUDED ROW RULES IN THE STUB SCHEMA

Excluded behavior must be driven by data, not hardcoded in the UI.

Use these rules:

If row.excluded = true:
- budget renders as Excluded
- spend remains visible
- variance renders as --
- variancePercent renders as --
- status renders as Excluded or the existing neutral excluded state
- downstream child rows under that excluded GL path must also be excluded when their budget meaning is derived solely from that excluded GL

Do not hardcode excluded presentation separately from the data source.

8. DEFINE DRILL STATE THROUGH childViewId

Do not hardcode drill results into UI components.

Drill must be driven by:
- row.childViewId
- reportState.activeViewId

When a user drills into a row:
- the UI must render the reportViews record identified by childViewId
- breadcrumbPath and scopeLabel must come from that child view record
- KPI values must come from that child view record
- rows must come from that child view record

9. DEFINE TIME-BUCKET DATA IN THE STUB LAYER

Each row.timeBuckets must be an ordered collection of bucket values for the active Timeframe + View By state.

Each time bucket record must contain:
- id
- label
- value

Use these meanings:
- id: unique bucket identifier
- label: visible bucket label such as Mar 1 to 7, Jan, or Q1
- value: the active metric’s consumed value for that bucket

Do not generate time-bucket columns from hardcoded UI examples.

10. DEFINE KPI FORMATTING INPUTS AS RAW VALUES

Store KPI and row values in raw numeric form in the stubbed data.
Do not preformat them as display strings.

The UI may format them according to already-established rules:
- PPD uses numeric PPD formatting
- Dollars use $ + commas + 2 decimals
- percentages remain percentages
- excluded states use Excluded / --

Do not embed old mock display strings into the data layer.

11. REMOVE ALL OLD HARDCODED MOCK DATA

Remove embedded mock values from UI components, including:
- hardcoded KPI values
- hardcoded breadcrumb text
- hardcoded scope text
- hardcoded row labels
- hardcoded row numbers
- hardcoded excluded examples
- hardcoded drill examples

Do not leave old values as fallback defaults.

12. BIND THE UI ONLY TO THE EXPLICIT STUB SCHEMA

After implementing the schema:
- UI components must read from the stubbed data layer only
- the visible report must reflect reportState + reportViews + entities
- no old direct mock values may remain embedded in presentation components

